            "videoId": "SdkhVQZGSSU",
            "textDisplay": "My mother, an English professor, used to tell me when I would start to argue with her back in my oh-so-wise teens, "Define your terms."  She would also say, "That's very high on the abstraction ladder."  \u003cbr\u003e"Racism" is a very abstract term used by many different people in many different ways to apply to their personal or tribal or national conception of things.  As several people have pointed out in the comments, much more ably than I could have, the definition is loose, flexible and vague,  and based on historical and cultural influences.  So, without a clear and very precise definition understood by all taking part in the conversation, there is always going to be trouble.  My compliments to a goodly number of commenters here!",

            "textDisplay": "This show has certainly brought the Internet Accuracy Police out in droves. In my view this was a great watch and well up to the standard set by Line of Duty, Bodyguard, Broadchurch and other recent UK TV dramas. Instead of criticising, let's mention the many things Vigil got right - the acting, plotting and pacing were all top notch. Not being homophobic, I didn't care that the central relationship involved a same-sex couple and found the chemistry between the two very believable and allowed me to care what happened to them. The exterior views of the boat recognisably showed a Vanguard class submarine. The murder of a Royal Navy crewman in UK territorial waters does fall under the jurisdiction of the UK civil police, as demonstrated by the investigation by Hampshire Police of a murder aboard HMS Astute in April 2011. There may be an exception to that in the case of a nuclear-armed submarine on patrolbut it's not an exception that will be made known to anyone other than a handful of people, for fairly obvious reasons. In the interests of balance, let's tick off some of the inaccuracies: the interior of Vigil was way too digital and way too spacious. The uniforms aren't accurate. Segregated female accommodation didn't happen in boats built in the 1980s -  the first RN submarines to be built with separate female quarters will be the Dreadnought class, which will replace the Vanguard class. Crew members on Vanguard class boats "hot bunk" meaning they share bunks. But the needs of accuracy often conflict with the needs of compelling drama, so compromises need to be made. There needed to be a visually compelling atmosphere inside Vigil. Cast members needed the space to interact. They didn't need the complication of trying to work out which of the bunk-sharing crew members had stowed the drugs. And so on. Honestly guys, enjoy the show on its merits. Or watch something else.",
